{"title_page": "Alceste C\u0153uriot", "text_new": "'''Alceste Anastasie Hortense C\u0153uriot''', also known under the stage name '''Madame Isma\u00ebl''', (born 1823 in [[Amsterdam]], The Netherlands; died 1893 in [[Colombes]], France) was a French operatic [[mezzo-soprano]]. Her professional career ran from 1850 to 1888 under the last name '''Isma\u00ebl''', which was her husband [[Jean-Vital Jammes]]' stage name, and she would keep the stage name even after their divorce in 1860. Throughout her onstage roles, she mostly portrayed roles of comic old women, \"du\u00e8gne\" roles, or \"[[Louise-Rosalie Lefebvre|Dugazon]]\" roles, which were of young mothers and women past youth.\n\n== Early life and marriage ==\nAlceste C\u0153uriot was born in 1823 to French [[tenor]] singer Paul-Joseph C\u0153uriot and French [[Lyric soprano|lyric]] singer Victoire Marie Fran\u00e7oise Lestage. Due to their professional careers, Alceste was born in [[Amsterdam]], The Netherlands.\n\nAround 1850, Paul-Joseph joined the [[Op\u00e9ra National de Lyon]], where his daughter also became a boarder. There, she met the [[baritone]] Isma\u00ebl, who joined Lyon in the summer of 1851, and on 24 January 1852, she married him in the Guilloti\u00e8re neighborhood of Lyon. They continued their careers as a couple \u2013 first at Lyon, next at the [[Grand Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de Bordeaux]], and finally at the [[Op\u00e9ra de Marseille]] in 1854. However, from 1854 on, their marriage was troubled, and C\u0153uriot asked for and obtained a separation in 1860 at the expense of Isma\u00ebl. As early as the first half of 1856, C\u0153uriot no longer appeared on the attendance lists of the Op\u00e9ra de Marseille next to him.<ref group=\"notes\">Judgment of \"separation\" kept in the departmental archives of the Bouches du Rh\u00f4ne.</ref>\n\n== Career, lawsuit, retirement, and death ==\n[[File:Death certificate of Alceste COEURIOT - 1893.jpg|thumb|C\u0153uriot's death certificate, issued in 1893.|alt=An archival black and white scan of a handwritten death certificate for Alceste C\u0153uriot from the village of Colombes. It is overlaid with a blue seal and bordered by white with archival information in the lower corners.]]C\u0153uriot's career continued as she played typecast parts, first \"[[Louise-Rosalie Lefebvre|Dugazon]]\" roles and then roles as comic old women, or \"du\u00e8gne\"<ref group=\"notes\">See [[:fr:Emploi (th\u00e9\u00e2tre)#Du\u00e8gne|Emploi (th\u00e9\u00e2tre)]] on French Wikipedia.</ref> roles. After working in numerous French theaters, she settled in [[Brussels]], at [[La Monnaie]], from 1875 to 1885. She is shown in [[Jacques Isnardon]]'s paintings of La Monnaie's troupes in 1875-1876, 1878-1879, 1879-1880 and 1884-1885.<ref>Isnardon p. 552, 572, 579, 607</ref> Isnardon also specifies her rate of pay during the years of 1877-1878, 1879-1880, and 1880-1881:<ref>Isnardon p. 571, 581, 586</ref> 500 francs.<ref group=\"notes\">At that time, Belgian francs were equal in value to French francs; the countries were part of the [[Latin Union]].</ref>\n\nWhile she was in Belgium, she could not be found in France by judicial authorities; however, Isma\u00ebl requested a divorce as soon as she returned to the jurisdiction of French law so that he could marry one of his younger students. The divorce was enforced by default in [[Marseille]] on 30 March 1885. During the 1885-1886 season, C\u0153uriot performed at the [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre du Capitole]] in [[Toulouse]], where she found she would be working alongside Isma\u00ebl's second wife, [[Marie Isma\u00ebl-Garcin]]. In 1886, they performed together in [[Faust (opera)|Faust]] by [[Charles Gounod]], both still using Isma\u00ebl's name. Her former husband sued her at the civil court of Toulouse; he refused to let C\u0153uriot continue to perform under this name, believing that his position was lawful because of their divorce. At court, C\u0153uriot won a definitive right to perform as \"Madam Isma\u00ebl\", which had been her stage name since 1852. Garcin, the second wife, would then be called \"Isma\u00ebl-Garcin\".<ref>Armand Silvestre, [[iarchive:p1gazetteanecd1886pariuoft|''Deux femmes pour un mari'']] in Georges d'Heylli (dir.) ''Gazette anecdotique, litt\u00e9raire, artistique et bibliographique'', vol. 1, Paris, Librairie des bibliophiles, 1886, p. 213.</ref><ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k231022t/f4.zoom.r=Isma%C3%ABl.langFR ''Le Temps'', 5 mai 1886], expos\u00e9 de l\u2019affaire, {{Gallica}}</ref><ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k231043w/f3.zoom.r=Isma%C3%ABl.langFR ''Le Temps'', 26 mai 1886], the civil court's judgement, {{Gallica}}</ref><ref>Hippolyte-Ferr\u00e9ol Rivi\u00e8re, [https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k5744564p/f15 \u00ab Acteurs : Propri\u00e9t\u00e9  des noms et pseudonymes \u00bb], ''Pandectes fran\u00e7aises : Nouveau r\u00e9pertoire de doctrine, de l\u00e9gislation et de jurisprudence'', vol. 2, Paris, Chevalier-Marescq, 1887, p. 6-8, {{Gallica}}.</ref>\n\nIn 1887, C\u0153uriot joined the [[Vlaamse Opera]], where she would perform at least until 1888. In 1886, she performed ''La petite Fadette'' at the [[Alhambra-Maurice Chevalier|Th\u00e9\u00e2tre du Ch\u00e2teau-d'Eau]]<ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k231111d/f4.zoom.r=Isma%C3%ABl.langFR ''Le Temps'', 3 ao\u00fbt 1886, Ch\u00e2teau d\u2019eau, ''La petite Fadette''], {{Gallica}}</ref> and at the [[Alhambra (Paris)|Op\u00e9ra-Populaire]]<ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k2314481/f3.zoom.r=Isma%C3%ABl.langFR ''Le Temps'', 1 juillet 1887, Op\u00e9ra Populaire, ''La petite Fadette''], {{Gallica}}</ref> in 1887.<ref group=\"notes\">Both these names refer to the [[Alhambra (Paris)]] of the 20th century, which was demolished in 1967.</ref> On 26 June 1889, the pension granted to C\u0153uriot by an association of dramatic artists was closed during a general meeting of the association.<ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k232201n/f3.zoom.r=Isma%C3%ABl.langFR ''Le Temps'', 26 juin 1889, Association des artistes dramatiques], {{Gallica}}</ref> This could be considered as a sign that she had retired. In 1892, one Madame Isma\u00ebl living on Ch\u00e2tillon Avenue in Paris \"pulled\" her pocketbook.<ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k233373d/f3.zoom.r=Isma%C3%ABl.langFR Le Temps, 7 juin 1892], {{Gallica}}</ref> Her death certificate was issued 17 April 1893.<ref>[http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Death_certificate_of_Alceste_COEURIOT_-_1893.jpg Acte de d\u00e9c\u00e8s d'Alceste C\u0153uriot, 17 avril 1893]</ref> She had lived in [[Colombes]], France, at 232 Victor Hugo Road, apparently in the company of another lyric artist, 54-year old Pascal Masson. She left no known living descendants.\n\n== Repertoire ==\n'''Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de la Monnaie, Bruxelles (1875-1885)'''\n\n*Madame Tidmann in ''Piccolino'' by [[Victorien Sardou]], 4 November 1876<ref>[[Jacques Isnardon]], [https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k54972877/f601.image.r=Isma%C3%ABl ''Le th\u00e9\u00e2tre de la Monnaie, depuis sa fondation jusqu\u2019\u00e0 nos jours'', p. 562]</ref>\n\n'''Th\u00e9\u00e2tre du Capitole de Toulouse (1886)'''\n\n*Marthe in ''[[Faust (opera)|Faust]]'' by [[Charles Gounod]], 1886\n\n'''Th\u00e9\u00e2tre du Ch\u00e2teau-d'Eau (1886 / 1887 - devenu Op\u00e9ra Populaire)'''\n\n*''[[La Petite Fadette|La petite Fadette]],'' 1886, 1887\n\n'''Th\u00e9\u00e2tre royal d\u2019Anvers (1880 / 1887-1888)'''\n\n* ''[[La dame blanche]]'' by [[Fran\u00e7ois Adrien Boieldieu]], 26 September 1880<ref group=\"notes\">She was credited as \u00ab Madame Isma\u00ebl de Bruxelles \u00bb</ref>\n* ''Le c\u0153ur et la main'' by [[Charles Lecocq]], 28 January 1887\n* ''Jos\u00e9phine vendue par ses s\u0153urs'' by [[Victor Roger]], 25 February 1887\n* ''Liederick'', 24 February 1888\n* ''[[Patrie! (opera)|Patrie !]]'' by [[\u00c9mile Paladilhe]], 6 March 1888\n* ''[[Mam'zelle Nitouche]]'' by [[Herv\u00e9 (composer)|Herv\u00e9]], 22 March 1888\n\n<small>'''Source''' : ''Historique complet du th\u00e9\u00e2tre royal d\u2019Anvers'', unless otherwise indicated</small>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=notes}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* {{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/lhistoriquecompl00gersuoft#page/n1/mode/2up|title=Historique complet du th\u00e9\u00e2tre royal d\u2019Anvers, 1804-1913|last=de Gers|first=Arthur|publisher=De Vos et Van der Groen|year=|isbn=|location=Antwerp|pages=|format=digitized images}} Accessible via the [[iarchive:robarts|University of Toronto, Robarts Library]]. \n* {{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/search.php?query=Gazette%20anecdotique%2C%20litt%C3%A9raire%2C%20artistique%20et%20bibliographique%20AND%20collection%3Atoronto|title=Gazette anecdotique, litt\u00e9raire, artistique et bibliographique|last=Heylli|first=Georges|display-authors=et al|publisher=Librairie des bibliophiles|year=1876-1891|isbn=|location=Paris|pages=|language=french|format=digitized images}} Accessible via the [[iarchive:robarts|University of Toronto, Robarts Library]]. \n* {{Cite book|url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k54972877.image.r=Isma%C3%ABl.f4|title=Le Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de la Monnaie, depuis sa fondation jusqu\u2019\u00e0 nos jours|last=Isnardon|first=Jacques|publisher=Schott fr\u00e8res \u00e9diteurs|year=1890|isbn=|location=Brussels|pages=|format=digitized images}} Accessible via [https://gallica.bnf.fr/ Gallica].\n* {{Cite news|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb34431794k/date.langFR|title=Les Temps|last=|first=|date=1861-1942|work=|access-date=}} Accessible via [https://gallica.bnf.fr/ Gallica].\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:C\u0153uriot, Alceste}}\n[[Category:1823 births]]\n[[Category:1893 deaths]]\n[[Category:French operatic mezzo-sopranos]]\n[[Category:19th-century French opera singers]]\n[[Category:Operatic mezzo-sopranos]]\n[[Category:19th-century women singers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Alceste Anastasie Hortense C\u0153uriot''', also known under the stage name '''Madame Isma\u00ebl''', (born 1823 in [[Amsterdam]], The Netherlands; died 1893 in [[Colombes]], France) was a French operatic [[mezzo-soprano]]. Her professional career ran from 1850 to 1888 under the last name '''Isma\u00ebl''', which was her husband [[Jean-Vital Jammes]]' stage name, and she would keep the stage name even after their divorce in 1860. Throughout her onstage roles, she mostly portrayed roles of comic old women, \"du\u00e8gne\" roles, or \"[[Louise-Rosalie Lefebvre|Dugazon]]\" roles, which were of young mothers and women past youth.\n\n== Early life and marriage ==\nAlceste C\u0153uriot was born in 1823 to French [[tenor]] singer Paul-Joseph C\u0153uriot and French [[Lyric soprano|lyric]] singer Victoire Marie Fran\u00e7oise Lestage. Due to their professional careers, Alceste was born in [[Amsterdam]], The Netherlands.\n\nAround 1850, Paul-Joseph joined the [[Op\u00e9ra National de Lyon]], where his daughter also became a boarder. There, she met the [[baritone]] Isma\u00ebl, who joined Lyon in the summer of 1851, and on 24 January 1852, she married him in the Guilloti\u00e8re neighborhood of Lyon. They continued their careers as a couple \u2013 first at Lyon, next at the [[Grand Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de Bordeaux]], and finally at the [[Op\u00e9ra de Marseille]] in 1854. However, from 1854 on, their marriage was troubled, and C\u0153uriot asked for and obtained a separation in 1860 at the expense of Isma\u00ebl. As early as the first half of 1856, C\u0153uriot no longer appeared on the attendance lists of the Op\u00e9ra de Marseille next to him.<ref group=\"notes\">Judgment of \"separation\" kept in the departmental archives of the Bouches du Rh\u00f4ne.</ref>\n\n== Career, lawsuit, retirement, and death ==\n[[File:Death certificate of Alceste COEURIOT - 1893.jpg|thumb|C\u0153uriot's death certificate, issued in 1893.|alt=An archival black and white scan of a handwritten death certificate for Alceste C\u0153uriot from the village of Colombes. It is overlaid with a blue seal and bordered by white with archival information in the lower corners.]]C\u0153uriot's career continued as she played typecast parts, first \"[[Louise-Rosalie Lefebvre|Dugazon]]\" roles and then roles as comic old women, or \"du\u00e8gne\"<ref group=\"notes\">See [[:fr:Emploi (th\u00e9\u00e2tre)#Du\u00e8gne|Emploi (th\u00e9\u00e2tre)]] on French Wikipedia.</ref> roles. After working in numerous French theaters, she settled in [[Brussels]], at [[La Monnaie]], from 1875 to 1885. She is shown in [[Jacques Isnardon]]'s paintings of La Monnaie's troupes in 1875-1876, 1878-1879, 1879-1880 and 1884-1885.<ref>Isnardon p. 552, 572, 579, 607</ref> Isnardon also specifies her rate of pay during the years of 1877-1878, 1879-1880, and 1880-1881:<ref>Isnardon p. 571, 581, 586</ref> 500 francs.<ref group=\"notes\">At that time, Belgian francs were equal in value to French francs; the countries were part of the [[Latin Union]].</ref>\n\nWhile she was in Belgium, she could not be found in France by judicial authorities; however, Isma\u00ebl requested a divorce as soon as she returned to the jurisdiction of French law so that he could marry one of his younger students. The divorce was enforced by default in [[Marseille]] on 30 March 1885. During the 1885-1886 season, C\u0153uriot performed at the [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre du Capitole]] in [[Toulouse]], where she found she would be working alongside Isma\u00ebl's second wife, [[Marie Isma\u00ebl-Garcin]]. In 1886, they performed together in [[Faust (opera)|Faust]] by [[Charles Gounod]], both still using Isma\u00ebl's name. Her former husband sued her at the civil court of Toulouse; he refused to let C\u0153uriot continue to perform under this name, believing that his position was lawful because of their divorce. At court, C\u0153uriot won a definitive right to perform as \"Madam Isma\u00ebl\", which had been her stage name since 1852. Garcin, the second wife, would then be called \"Isma\u00ebl-Garcin\".<ref>Armand Silvestre, [[iarchive:p1gazetteanecd1886pariuoft|''Deux femmes pour un mari'']] in Georges d'Heylli (dir.) ''Gazette anecdotique, litt\u00e9raire, artistique et bibliographique'', vol. 1, Paris, Librairie des bibliophiles, 1886, p. 213.</ref><ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k231022t/f4.zoom.r=Isma%C3%ABl.langFR ''Le Temps'', 5 mai 1886], expos\u00e9 de l\u2019affaire, {{Gallica}}</ref><ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k231043w/f3.zoom.r=Isma%C3%ABl.langFR ''Le Temps'', 26 mai 1886], the civil court's judgement, {{Gallica}}</ref><ref>Hippolyte-Ferr\u00e9ol Rivi\u00e8re, [https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k5744564p/f15 \u00ab Acteurs : Propri\u00e9t\u00e9  des noms et pseudonymes \u00bb], ''Pandectes fran\u00e7aises : Nouveau r\u00e9pertoire de doctrine, de l\u00e9gislation et de jurisprudence'', vol. 2, Paris, Chevalier-Marescq, 1887, p. 6-8, {{Gallica}}.</ref>\n\nIn 1887, C\u0153uriot joined the [[Vlaamse Opera]], where she would perform at least until 1888. In 1886, she performed ''La petite Fadette'' at the [[Alhambra-Maurice Chevalier|Th\u00e9\u00e2tre du Ch\u00e2teau-d'Eau]]<ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k231111d/f4.zoom.r=Isma%C3%ABl.langFR ''Le Temps'', 3 ao\u00fbt 1886, Ch\u00e2teau d\u2019eau, ''La petite Fadette''], {{Gallica}}</ref> and at the [[Alhambra (Paris)|Op\u00e9ra-Populaire]]<ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k2314481/f3.zoom.r=Isma%C3%ABl.langFR ''Le Temps'', 1 juillet 1887, Op\u00e9ra Populaire, ''La petite Fadette''], {{Gallica}}</ref> in 1887.<ref group=\"notes\">Both these names refer to the [[Alhambra (Paris)]] of the 20th century, which was demolished in 1967.</ref> On 26 June 1889, the pension granted to C\u0153uriot by an association of dramatic artists was closed during a general meeting of the association.<ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k232201n/f3.zoom.r=Isma%C3%ABl.langFR ''Le Temps'', 26 juin 1889, Association des artistes dramatiques], {{Gallica}}</ref> This could be considered as a sign that she had retired. In 1892, one Madame Isma\u00ebl living on Ch\u00e2tillon Avenue in Paris \"pulled\" her pocketbook.<ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k233373d/f3.zoom.r=Isma%C3%ABl.langFR Le Temps, 7 juin 1892], {{Gallica}}</ref> Her death certificate was issued 17 April 1893.<ref>[http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Death_certificate_of_Alceste_COEURIOT_-_1893.jpg Acte de d\u00e9c\u00e8s d'Alceste C\u0153uriot, 17 avril 1893]</ref> She had lived in [[Colombes]], France, at 232 Victor Hugo Road, apparently in the company of another lyric artist, 54-year old Pascal Masson. She left no known living descendants.\n\n== Repertoire ==\n'''Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de la Monnaie, Bruxelles (1875-1885)'''\n\n*Madame Tidmann in ''Piccolino'' by [[Victorien Sardou]], 4 November 1876<ref>[[Jacques Isnardon]], [https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k54972877/f601.image.r=Isma%C3%ABl ''Le th\u00e9\u00e2tre de la Monnaie, depuis sa fondation jusqu\u2019\u00e0 nos jours'', p. 562]</ref>\n\n'''Th\u00e9\u00e2tre du Capitole de Toulouse (1886)'''\n\n*Marthe in ''[[Faust (opera)|Faust]]'' by [[Charles Gounod]], 1886\n\n'''Th\u00e9\u00e2tre du Ch\u00e2teau-d'Eau (1886 / 1887 - devenu Op\u00e9ra Populaire)'''\n\n*''[[La Petite Fadette|La petite Fadette]],'' 1886, 1887\n\n'''Th\u00e9\u00e2tre royal d\u2019Anvers (1880 / 1887-1888)'''\n\n* ''[[La dame blanche]]'' by [[Fran\u00e7ois Adrien Boieldieu]], 26 September 1880<ref group=\"notes\">She was credited as \u00ab Madame Isma\u00ebl de Bruxelles \u00bb</ref>\n* ''Le c\u0153ur et la main'' by [[Charles Lecocq]], 28 January 1887\n* ''Jos\u00e9phine vendue par ses s\u0153urs'' by [[Victor Roger]], 25 February 1887\n* ''Liederick'', 24 February 1888\n* ''[[Patrie! (opera)|Patrie !]]'' by [[\u00c9mile Paladilhe]], 6 March 1888\n* ''[[Mam'zelle Nitouche]]'' by [[Herv\u00e9 (composer)|Herv\u00e9]], 22 March 1888\n\n<small>'''Source''' : ''Historique complet du th\u00e9\u00e2tre royal d\u2019Anvers'', unless otherwise indicated</small>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=notes}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* {{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/lhistoriquecompl00gersuoft#page/n1/mode/2up|title=Historique complet du th\u00e9\u00e2tre royal d\u2019Anvers, 1804-1913|last=de Gers|first=Arthur|publisher=De Vos et Van der Groen|year=|isbn=|location=Antwerp|pages=|format=digitized images}} Accessible via the [[iarchive:robarts|University of Toronto, Robarts Library]]. \n* {{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/search.php?query=Gazette%20anecdotique%2C%20litt%C3%A9raire%2C%20artistique%20et%20bibliographique%20AND%20collection%3Atoronto|title=Gazette anecdotique, litt\u00e9raire, artistique et bibliographique|last=Heylli|first=Georges|display-authors=et al|publisher=Librairie des bibliophiles|year=1876-1891|isbn=|location=Paris|pages=|language=french|format=digitized images}} Accessible via the [[iarchive:robarts|University of Toronto, Robarts Library]]. \n* {{Cite book|url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k54972877.image.r=Isma%C3%ABl.f4|title=Le Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de la Monnaie, depuis sa fondation jusqu\u2019\u00e0 nos jours|last=Isnardon|first=Jacques|publisher=Schott fr\u00e8res \u00e9diteurs|year=1890|isbn=|location=Brussels|pages=|format=digitized images}} Accessible via [https://gallica.bnf.fr/ Gallica].\n* {{Cite news|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb34431794k/date.langFR|title=Les Temps|last=|first=|date=1861-1942|work=|access-date=}} Accessible via [https://gallica.bnf.fr/ Gallica].\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:C\u0153uriot, Alceste}}\n[[Category:1823 births]]\n[[Category:1893 deaths]]\n[[Category:French operatic mezzo-sopranos]]\n[[Category:19th-century French opera singers]]\n[[Category:Operatic mezzo-sopranos]]\n[[Category:19th-century women singers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBibliography:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alceste_C%C5%93uriot"}
{"title_page": "Pasquale Bruti", "text_new": "'''Pasquale Bruti''' (lat. ''Paschalis Dabrus'')<ref>{{cite book |last1=Conference |first1=American Association of Teachers of Italian |title=Italiana: Selected Papers from the Proceeedings of the ... Annual Conference of the American Association of Teachers of Italian |date=1988 |publisher=Rosary College |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=dSBdAAAAMAAJ&dq=Pasquale+Dabro&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Pasquale |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>   also known as '''Pasquale Dabri''' or '''Dragoman Pasquale''' (died 1596, Belgrad) was an Albanian dragoman and Venetian interpreter from the 16th century.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Brown |first1=Rawdon Lubbock |title=Calendar of State Papers and Manuscripts, Relating to English Affairs Existing in the Archives and Collection of Venice, and in Other Libraries of Northern Italy |date=1970 |publisher=Longman, Green, Longman, Roberts, and Green |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=5wA2AQAAMAAJ&q=Pasquale+Bruti&dq=Pasquale+Bruti&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiV2_fZze3oAhWAwMQBHRKUDDUQ6AEITjAE |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> He was part of the Dabri family, who later married into the Bruti family. Pasquale was the nephew of [[Bartolomeo Bruti]]. In 1596, [[Edward Barton (diplomat)|Edward Barton]], the English ambassador in Istanbul, travelled with the Ottoman sultan [[Mehmed III]] through Hungary with his dragoman, Pasquale Bruti. He served the Ottoman court for 40 years until he was assassinated in Belgrad in 1596 by the Ottoman captain Hassan Pasha who suspected that Bruti was a spy. Pasquale was the son of Marco Dabri and Lucietta Bruti, who intermarried with the [[Bruti family|Brutis]]. a Venetian publication from 1755 mentions that Pasquale was \u201c''in ea urbe longe princeps''\u201d (by far the best) among the eminent personalities of Dulcigno (Ulcinj).<ref>{{cite book |title=Studi storici |date=1980 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=K3loAAAAMAAJ&q=Pasquale+Dabro&dq=Pasquale+Dabro&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi42uq20O3oAhX78KYKHZpPDpkQ6AEIUzAE |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=it}}</ref>\n\n==Dragoman and the Bruti family==\nPasquale Bruti worked for the Ottomans in maintaining relations between the Ottomans, and the European powers, such as England, Hungary, Venice and Wallachia. Bruti also helped negotiate the release of prisoners of the Imperial Embassy in Constantinople, among them the captured Habsburg ambassador [[Friedrich von Kreckwitz |Friedrich von Kreckwitz (1568-1637) ]] and his staff. Bruti arrived in Vienna with two Turkish soldiers where negotiations carried on until December that year. Bruti wrote three letters, one to the Sultan, one to the Grand Vizier and one to Barton. The results of these negotiations are not known. Although the documentation of Bruti is rare, the Venetian ambassador in Prague mentions him as \u201cBruti\u201d while his college Marco Venier mentions him as \u201cDabrik\u201d. Pasquale Bruti was part of the Dabris, an ancient Albanian noble family from Ulcinj.\n\nOn December 1591, Pasquale is mentioned as a relative to Cristoforo Bruti and Bartolomeo Bruti. After Bartolomeo Bruti was murdered by the Voivode of Wallachia, his brother Cristoforo took over. After he died, the newphew Pasquale took over in 1592. During this time, he was acquainted with Barton, Queen Elisabeths closest man. Barton entrusted Bruti to arrange the release of Viennese prisoners in 1596, ordered by [[Matthias, Holy Roman Emperor|Archduke Matthias, the Holy Roman Emperor]]. For some reason, Barton was angry at Bruti and wrote to the Venetian ambassador that \u201c''of our people that went in his suite Pasquale Dabri, whom I had to dismiss for reasons which really merited severer punishment''\u201d.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Malcolm |first1=Noel |title=Agents of Empire: Knights, Corsairs, Jesuits and Spies in the Sixteenth-Century Mediterranean World |date=2015 |publisher=Penguin Books Limited |isbn=978-0-14-197836-9 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=KHKKBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT789&lpg=PT789&dq=Pasquale+Bruti+1597&source=bl&ots=JSjluaRbCh&sig=ACfU3U18G8-0kz4QdAdgRNdXah9QA7NE3Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjggPjCue3oAhUs86YKHVKyBUQQ6AEwAHoECAsQKQ#v=onepage&q=Pasquale%20Bruti&f=false |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Venetian interpretor and ambassador for Ottomans and Habsburg==\nIn 1592, a report from Issue mentions that Pasquale was sent by Cristoforo Bruti to the Moldavian capital to marry a young woman from the house of Benedetto (or possibly Bartolomeo) Bruti, and this Pasquale was married to the Brutis. Pasquale then moved ot Istanbul where he continued the work of Cristoforo after he died. Here, Pasquale also helped his brother Marin Dabri who settled in Pera. While in Istanbul, Bruti quickly learned the Turkish language.<ref>{{cite book |title=Does the Drina flow cultural indifference and Slovene Yugoslav literature in Turkish |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/275759461_Does_the_Drina_flow_Cultural_indifference_and_SloveneYugoslav_literature_in_Turkish/link/5678138308ae125516ee6482/download |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> In July 20, 1596, Bruti left Constantinople with Barton. The Venetian ambassador in Prague continued to mention Bruti in various reports and he informed the Venetian ambassador of Brutis arrival daily. [[Maximilian II, Holy Roman Emperor]] did not trust Bruti or Barton as he believed they had come to spy, and asked Bruti to return to Vienna. After having checked with other sources of Brutis intentions, he was allowed to return.\n\nTensions between Hungary and Ottomans led to the refusal of peace. According to Bruti, the Ottoman troops were ready for further expansion towards the Hungarian frontier, risking confrontations by Tatars. Vendramin had supposedly lost the chance of peace when the Ottomans had difficulties in the Balkans. Eventually, the Venetian ambassador met Bruti in person and told him of the Ottomans intentions and the army, consisting of 200,000 men, lacking guns for siege. There were also tension between the Spahi forces and the Janissaries who almost clashed with each other. Bruti then informed Vendramine that Archduke Maximilian II and the emperors agent had negotiated with him several times but with no success. Apparently, the conditions for peace were unachievable due to request of returning the previous Sultan. According to Bruti, in order to have peace, the Emperor would have to return Esztergom and V\u00e1c and a sum of money. However the situation was tense as the Emperor had lost the empires \u201ceyes\u201d with the loss of said territories. Vendramin trusted Bruti, however, he was bothered that he did not know Brutis origins, who had left Albania for four years.\n\nMutual distrust appeared between the monarchs and the Ottoman threat made the vote for German imperial aid more likely, which encouraged Habsburg and the Holy See to prove financial aid. Though poorly documented, it seems that Vendramins words regarding the letters entrusted to Bruti suggest that the Emperor did not give Bruti a chance to reach an agreement. Despite these events, the Spanish king did not want to engage in the Mediterranean war. In June 1597, Barton waited for Bruti in Constantinople and he did not arrive. Sigismund Bathory then wrote to a Turkish correspondent who said that Bruti had been stopped by the Pasha of Budua.<ref>{{cite book |title=Revue roumaine d'histoire |date=1989 |publisher=Editions de l'Acad\u00e9mie de la R\u00e9publique socialiste de Roumanie |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=K-3TAAAAMAAJ&q=Pasquale+Bruti&dq=Pasquale+Bruti&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjJ1Jn9ze3oAhXj-yoKHZbMCJs4ChDoAQg5MAI |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=fr}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nMeanwhile, Bruti and his entourage travelled to Belgrade, on a peace mission organised by Zsigmond B\u00e1thori and Mih\u00e1ly Vit\u00e9z, the voivode of Havasalf\u00f6ld.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Krappas |first1=Tamas |title=OKM\u00c1NYOK \u00c9S IRATOK A TIZEN\u00d6T \u00c9VES H\u00c1BOR\u00da ID\u0150SZAK\u00c1B\u00d3L (1594-1597)* |url=https://institutumfraknoi.hu/sites/default/files/2019-01/lk_76_2005.2_330-371.pdf |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> \nHere his fate would meat a tragic end. Hassan Pasha, an Ottoman commander who was staying in the city preparing for the Ottoman offensive, arrested Pasquale Bruti and executed him in unclear circumstances. It turned out that Hassan Pasha of Belgrade wanted to continue the war with Habsburg at any costs, which Brutis peace negotiations seemed to end.<ref>{{cite book |title=From Pax Mongolica to Pax Ottomanica: War, Religion and Trade in the Northwestern Black Sea Region (14th-16th Centuries) |date=2020 |publisher=BRILL |isbn=978-90-04-42244-5 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=RxfUDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA237&lpg=PA237&dq=Pasquale+Bruti&source=bl&ots=rplqHeuGN3&sig=ACfU3U16HVvirDIVa20Ve6PrZ3HDz77XuQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi6z-LbzO3oAhUDwsQBHQ2FD5AQ6AEwAXoECAsQMQ#v=onepage&q=Pasquale%20Bruti&f=false |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>  Alongn with Bruti was Ali Cha, traveling from [[Gyulafeh\u00e9rv\u00e1r]] to Constantinople. It would seem that Hassan Pasha had acted according to his own interest, as he was upset of the betrayal initiated by the English Ambassador and Ibrahim Pasha, a rival of Hassan Pasha. He apparently thought that the execution of Bruti would make negotiations with the English impossible, however, the Sultan rewarded Ibrahim Pasha by making him Grand Vizier. At the same time, Bruti's persecution provided an opportunity for the imperial court to put pressure on the King of Spain, who, for the reasons mentioned above, did not want to engage in war in the Mediterranean. Hassan Pasha now feared that if he returned, the Vizier would be furious for the death of Bruti, and then force the Sultan to punish Hassan Pasha. The  The Vizier made two attempts on Hassans life but failed. Hassan then testified to the dragoman of the Venetian ambassador that Pasquale Bruti was not dead, which was the last time Bruti was mentioned again.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bruti, Pasquale}}\n[[Category:1598 deaths]]\n[[Category:Albanian diplomats]]\n[[Category:People from Ulcinj]]\n[[Category:Albanian spies]]\n", "text_old": "'''Pasquale Bruti''' (lat. ''Paschalis Dabrus'')<ref>{{cite book |last1=Conference |first1=American Association of Teachers of Italian |title=Italiana: Selected Papers from the Proceeedings of the ... Annual Conference of the American Association of Teachers of Italian |date=1988 |publisher=Rosary College |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=dSBdAAAAMAAJ&dq=Pasquale+Dabro&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Pasquale |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\u2028\u2028 also known as '''Pasquale Dabri''' or '''Dragoman Pasquale''' (died 1596, Belgrad) was an Albanian dragoman and Venetian interpreter from the 16th century.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Brown |first1=Rawdon Lubbock |title=Calendar of State Papers and Manuscripts, Relating to English Affairs Existing in the Archives and Collection of Venice, and in Other Libraries of Northern Italy |date=1970 |publisher=Longman, Green, Longman, Roberts, and Green |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=5wA2AQAAMAAJ&q=Pasquale+Bruti&dq=Pasquale+Bruti&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiV2_fZze3oAhWAwMQBHRKUDDUQ6AEITjAE |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> He was part of the Dabri family, who later married into the Bruti family. Pasquale was the nephew of [[Bartolomeo Bruti]]. In 1596, [[Edward Barton (diplomat)|Edward Barton]], the English ambassador in Istanbul, travelled with the Ottoman sultan [[Mehmed III]] through Hungary with his dragoman, Pasquale Bruti. He served the Ottoman court for 40 years until he was assassinated in Belgrad in 1596 by the Ottoman captain Hassan Pasha who suspected that Bruti was a spy. Pasquale was the son of Marco Dabri and Lucietta Bruti, who intermarried with the [[Bruti family|Brutis]]. a Venetian pu