war in the Mediterranean. Hassan Pasha now feared that if he returned, the Vizier would be furious for the death of Bruti, and then force the Sultan to punish Hassan Pasha. The  The Vizier made two attempts on Hassans life but failed. Hassan then testified to the dragoman of the Venetian ambassador that Pasquale Bruti was not dead, which was the last time Bruti was mentioned again.\n\n== References ==\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bruti, Pasquale}}\n[[Category:1598 deaths]]\n[[Category:Albanian diplomats]]\n[[Category:People from Ulcinj]]\n[[Category:People from Ulcinj]]\n[[Category:Albanian spies]]\n{{Albania-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, removed stub tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pasquale_Bruti"}
{"title_page": "Margaret Clifford, Countess of Cumberland", "text_new": "{{nofootnotes|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2019}}\n[[File:Margaret, Countess of Cumberland from NPG.jpg|thumb|Portrait of Margaret Clifford, 1585]]\n'''Margaret Clifford''' (''n\u00e9e'' '''Russell'''), '''Countess of Cumberland''' (7 July 1560 \u2013 24 May 1616) was an English [[noblewoman]] and [[maid of honor]] to [[Elizabeth I]]. Lady Margaret was born in [[Exeter, England]] to [[Francis Russell, 2nd Earl of Bedford]] and Margaret St John.\n\nOn 24 June 1577 she married [[George Clifford, 3rd Earl of Cumberland]] the son of [[Henry Clifford, 2nd Earl of Cumberland]] and Anne Dacre. Her sister, [[Anne Russell, Countess of Warwick]], was married to [[Ambrose Dudley]], brother of [[Robert Dudley, 1st Earl of Leicester|Robert Dudley]], the [[Earl of Leicester]], and Anne too was a great literary patron and a close friend to [[Queen Elizabeth I]], attending her on her death bed.\n\nShe was a patron of the poet [[Emilia Lanier]].<ref>Helen Wilcox  ''1611: Authority, Gender, and the Word in Early Modern England'' (Chichester, 2014), pp. 55\u201356.</ref>\n\nIn 1593, Lady Margaret Russell founded [[Beamsley Hospital]], an almshouse for local widows. \n\nShe was interested in physic and alchemy, and had an alchemical recipe book compiled for her.<ref>Penny Bayer, 'Lady Margaret Clifford's Alchemical Receipt Book and the John Dee Circle', ''Ambix'', 52:3 (2005), pp. 274-284.</ref> \nVolume 52, 2005\n\nThe tomb of the Countess is at [[St Lawrence's Church, Appleby]] along with that of her daughter, [[Lady Anne Clifford, 14th Baroness de Clifford]]. Lady Anne Clifford built the [[Countess Pillar]] to commemorate her.\n\n==Children==\n* Sir Robert Clifford (21 September 1585 \u2013 24 May 1591)\n* Francis Clifford (1584 \u2013 8 December 1589)\n* [[Lady Anne Clifford]] (30 January 1590 \u2013 22 March 1676) married [[Richard Sackville, 3rd Earl of Dorset]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*Bell, J. ''Belle Assembl\u00e9e: Or, Court and Fashionable Magazine; Containing Interesting and Original Literature, and Records of the Beau-monde.'' Ser. 3, vol. 8, J. Bell, 1828. (p.&nbsp;238) [https://books.google.com/books?id=lcIRAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA236&dq=alchemy+margaret,+countess+of+cumberland&as_brr=1 googlebooks] Retrieved 11 September 2008\n*Walpole, Horace, and [[Thomas Park (antiquarian)|Thomas Park]]. ''A Catalogue of the Royal and Noble Authors of England, Scotland, and Ireland; With Lists of Their Works.'' London: Printed for J. Scott, 1806.  [https://books.google.com/books?id=bKrDLZLN3qkC&pg=PA175&lpg=PA175&dq=Lady+Margaret+Russell&source=web&ots=pKgp4CZe2O&sig=0sPoUEOWJsB64xpeRMeCsnMD9co&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=6&ct=result#PPA175,M1 googlebooks] Retrieved 31 August 2008\n\n==External links==\n* [http://emlo-portal.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/collections/?catalogue=margaret-clifford The Correspondence of Margaret Clifford], in [http://emlo.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/home EMLO]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cumberland, Margaret Clifford, Countess of}}\n[[Category:1560 births]]\n[[Category:1616 deaths]]\n[[Category:English countesses]]\n[[Category:British maids of honour]]\n[[Category:Women of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:16th-century English women]]\n[[Category:16th-century English nobility]]\n[[Category:17th-century English women]]\n[[Category:17th-century English nobility]]\n", "text_old": "{{nofootnotes|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2019}}\n[[File:Margaret, Countess of Cumberland from NPG.jpg|thumb|Portrait of Margaret Clifford, 1585]]\n'''Margaret Clifford''' (''n\u00e9e'' '''Russell'''), '''Countess of Cumberland''' (7 July 1560 \u2013 24 May 1616) was an English [[noblewoman]] and [[maid of honor]] to [[Elizabeth I]]. Lady Margaret was born in [[Exeter, England]] to [[Francis Russell, 2nd Earl of Bedford]] and Margaret St John.\n\nOn 24 June 1577 she married [[George Clifford, 3rd Earl of Cumberland]] the son of [[Henry Clifford, 2nd Earl of Cumberland]] and Anne Dacre. Her sister, [[Anne Russell, Countess of Warwick]], was married to [[Ambrose Dudley]], brother of [[Robert Dudley, 1st Earl of Leicester|Robert Dudley]], the [[Earl of Leicester]], and Anne too was a great literary patron and a close friend to [[Queen Elizabeth I]], attending her on her death bed.\n\nShe was a patron of the poet [[Emilia Lanier]].<ref>Helen Wilcox  ''1611: Authority, Gender, and the Word in Early Modern England'' (Chichester, 2014), pp. 55\u201356.</ref>\n\nIn 1593, Lady Margaret Russell founded [[Beamsley Hospital]], an almshouse for local widows. \n\nThe tomb of the Countess is at [[St Lawrence's Church, Appleby]] along with that of her daughter, [[Lady Anne Clifford, 14th Baroness de Clifford]]. Lady Anne Clifford built the [[Countess Pillar]] to commemorate her.\n\n==Children==\n* Sir Robert Clifford (21 September 1585 \u2013 24 May 1591)\n* Francis Clifford (1584 \u2013 8 December 1589)\n* [[Lady Anne Clifford]] (30 January 1590 \u2013 22 March 1676) married [[Richard Sackville, 3rd Earl of Dorset]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*Bell, J. ''Belle Assembl\u00e9e: Or, Court and Fashionable Magazine; Containing Interesting and Original Literature, and Records of the Beau-monde.'' Ser. 3, vol. 8, J. Bell, 1828. (p.&nbsp;238) [https://books.google.com/books?id=lcIRAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA236&dq=alchemy+margaret,+countess+of+cumberland&as_brr=1 googlebooks] Retrieved 11 September 2008\n*Walpole, Horace, and [[Thomas Park (antiquarian)|Thomas Park]]. ''A Catalogue of the Royal and Noble Authors of England, Scotland, and Ireland; With Lists of Their Works.'' London: Printed for J. Scott, 1806.  [https://books.google.com/books?id=bKrDLZLN3qkC&pg=PA175&lpg=PA175&dq=Lady+Margaret+Russell&source=web&ots=pKgp4CZe2O&sig=0sPoUEOWJsB64xpeRMeCsnMD9co&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=6&ct=result#PPA175,M1 googlebooks] Retrieved 31 August 2008\n\n==External links==\n* [http://emlo-portal.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/collections/?catalogue=margaret-clifford The Correspondence of Margaret Clifford], in [http://emlo.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/home EMLO]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cumberland, Margaret Clifford, Countess of}}\n[[Category:1560 births]]\n[[Category:1616 deaths]]\n[[Category:English countesses]]\n[[Category:British maids of honour]]\n[[Category:Women of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:16th-century English women]]\n[[Category:16th-century English nobility]]\n[[Category:17th-century English women]]\n[[Category:17th-century English nobility]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Margaret_Clifford,_Countess_of_Cumberland"}
{"title_page": "Fantasy Island (U.S. amusement park)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox amusement park\n| name = Fantasy Island\n| logo            = Fantasy Island Grand Island logo.png\n| logo_size       = \n| alt             = \n| logo_caption    = \n| image           = \n| image_size      =\n| slogan   = Fun. Done. Right.<small> (2016-2020)</small><br>50 Years of Family Fun<small> (2011-2016)</small><br>Spend the Day, Not a Fortune<small> (1994-2011)</small><br>Makes a Good Time Great!<small> (1986-1992)</small><br>Celebrate<small> (1982-1986)</small><br>Fun? Wow!<small> (1978-1982)</small><br>A Dream Come True<small> (1961-1978)</small>\n| location = 2400 Grand Island Boulevard\n| location2 = [[Grand Island, New York|Grand Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]] 14072\n| area = {{convert|85|acre|m2}}\n| status          = Closed \n| opening_date = July 1, 1961\n| closing_date    = February 19, 2020\n| previous_names  = Two Flags Over Niagara Fun Park <small>(1992-1994)</small><br>Martin's Fantasy Island <small>(1994\u20132016)</small>\n| owner = [[Apex Parks Group]] <small>(2016-2020)</small><br>Martin's Shows <small>(1994-2016) </small><br>International Broadcasting Corporation <small>(1989-1992)</small><br>[[Charles Wood (businessman)|Charles R. Wood Enterprises]] <small>(1982-1989, 1992-1994)</small><br>Fantasy Island, Inc. <small>(1961-1982)</small>\n| general_manager = \n| homepage = [http://www.fantasyislandny.com Official website]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|43|1|37.2|N|78|58|14.5|W|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Fantasy Island''' was an [[amusement park]] on [[Grand Island, New York]] from 1961 to 2020.\n\n==History==\n'''Fantasy Island''' was founded by real estate developer Lawrence Grant and opened in July 1961. It was designed by co-financier Gerald Birzon, a local jeweler, and constructed by Milton Milstein and Associates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MKOkQoVeGWAC&lpg=PA157&ots=dI3UV6pHqt&dq=%22Lawrence+Grant%22+%22fantasy+island%22&pg=PA157#v=onepage&q=%22Lawrence+Grant%22+%22fantasy+island%22&f=false|title=Amusement Parks of New York|first=Jim|last=Futrell|date=March 2, 2006|publisher=Stackpole Books|via=Google Books}}</ref> The ownership group was formed under the name Fantasy Land, Inc. before changing soon after to Fantasy Island, Inc. The group had originally planned to call the park '''Fantasy Land''', but changed the name for legal reasons after finding out there was already an area of [[Disneyland]] called [[Fantasyland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xtrLDCJYVsAC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PA77&dq=%22fantasy+land,+inc%22&pg=PA77#v=onepage&q=%22fantasy+land,+inc%22&f=false|title=Western New York Amusement Parks|first=Rose Ann|last=Hirsch|date=March 2, 2011|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nOriginally, the park occupied only {{convert|12|acre|m2}} of land that was divided into five themed areas: Action Town, Animal Kingdom, Garden of Fables, Indian Village, and Western Town.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/2011/07/08/theme-park-to-mark-50th-year-fantasy-island-plans-saturday-celebration/|title=Theme park to mark 50th year; Fantasy Island plans Saturday celebration|date=July 8, 2011}}</ref>  Western Town, a live [[Wild West shows|Wild West show]], remained a staple of the park throughout its existence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wgrz.com/article/entertainment/television/programs/most-buffalo/fantasy-island-reunion-western-town-alumni-reunite/71-81f6e7f9-260a-4979-8118-89a90a34a85a|title=Fantasy Island reunion: 'Western Town' alumni reunite|first=Pete|last=Gallivan|first2=Kate|last2=Welshofer|work=[[WGRZ]]|date=March 2, 2020|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> \n\nTo promote the park, [[WGR-TV]] aired a live weekly television program on Saturday mornings from 1961 to 1962 titled '''''Fantasy Island Show'''''. It featured the park's characters and puppeteers performing for an all-children studio audience. The show's host and protagonist was Buckskin Joe, portrayed by park general manager Clyde \"Buddy\" Farnan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.buffalostories.com/the-golden-age-of-kids-tv-in-buffalo/|title=The Golden Age of Kids\u2019 TV in Buffalo \u2013 Buffalo Stories Archives & Blog}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xtrLDCJYVsAC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PA87&dq=%22fantasy+island%22+wgr&pg=PA87#v=onepage&q=%22fantasy+island%22+wgr&f=false|title=Western New York Amusement Parks|first=Rose Ann|last=Hirsch|date=March 2, 2011|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nA 2,500-seat outdoor arena was constructed in 1965 for French [[lion tamer]] Jean \"Tarzan\" Zerbini's circus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MKOkQoVeGWAC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PA158&dq=%22fantasy+island%22+zerbini&pg=PA158#v=onepage&q=%22fantasy+island%22+zerbini&f=false|title=Amusement Parks of New York|first=Jim|last=Futrell|date=March 2, 2006|publisher=Stackpole Books|via=Google Books}}</ref> The park was expanded to {{convert|85|acre|m2}} in 1974 to make room for adult rides and broaden the park's appeal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MKOkQoVeGWAC&lpg=PA160&ots=dI3UV6qEpt&dq=%22fantasy+island%22+1974+%2285+acres%22&pg=PA160#v=onepage&q=%22fantasy+island%22+1974+%2285+acres%22&f=false|title=Amusement Parks of New York|first=Jim|last=Futrell|date=March 2, 2006|publisher=Stackpole Books|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nAfter dwindling attendance stemming from Western New York's [[rust belt]] economic decline, Fantasy Island, Inc. declared bankruptcy and the park did not operate for the 1982 season. It was acquired out of bankruptcy in November 1982 by Charles R. Wood Enterprises, headed by [[Charles Wood (businessman)|Charles Wood]], the founder of [[The Great Escape & Splashwater Kingdom|Great Escape]] in [[Queensbury, New York]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1982/11/23/Youngsters-need-those-summer-jobs/9758406875600/|title='Youngsters need those summer jobs'|website=UPI}}</ref> A new themed area called Water World, a [[water park]], was added to the site in 1984. Wood sold the park along with [[The Great Escape & Splashwater Kingdom|Great Escape]] to International Broadcasting Corporation (IBC) in April 1989 for $36 million dollars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MKOkQoVeGWAC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PA163&dq=%22international+broadcasting+corporation%22+%22fantasy+island%22&pg=PA163#v=onepage&q=%22international+broadcasting+corporation%22+%22fantasy+island%22&f=false|title=Amusement Parks of New York|first=Jim|last=Futrell|date=March 2, 2006|publisher=Stackpole Books|via=Google Books}}</ref> As part of the deal, Wood wood stay on as [[chief executive officer]] of the park and his son-in-law, Tom Wages, was retained as general manager.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://casetext.com/case/international-broadcasting-v-turner|title=International Broadcasting v. Turner, 734 F. Supp. 383 &#124; Casetext|website=casetext.com}}</ref> Following the closure of nearby [[Crystal Beach Amusement Park]], that park's famed [[Comet (Great Escape)|Comet]] roller coaster was purchased by Charles Wood at auction in October 1989 for $210,000, disassembled, and stored indefinitely at Fantasy Island.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/1989/10/18/the-comet-is-going-going-but-might-not-be-gone-210000-sale-may-bring-it-to-fantasy-island/|title=THE COMET IS GOING, GOING . . . BUT MIGHT NOT BE GONE $210,000 SALE MAY BRING IT TO FANTASY ISLAND|date=October 18, 1989}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1990, Michael Murach was paralyzed from the head down while performing a [[high diving]] act at the park. He slipped on a 3-meter diving board during a comedy act and fell 20-feet, hitting his head on the edge of the concrete pool. Murach was years later awarded damages of $58.6 million dollars after a jury found International Broadcasting Corporation 100% liable for his injury. The end of the diving board was not installed at a proper distance away from the edge of the pool to prevent such an incident from occurring. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/2003/12/03/paralyzed-ex-diver-awarded-58-6-million/|title=PARALYZED EX-DIVER AWARDED $58.6 MILLION|date=December 3, 2003}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1991, 14-year-old Kenneth Margerum fell {{convert|60|ft}} to his death from the park's [[Ferris wheel]] after his seat dropped from its axle. It was revealed that the park operators routinely removed one or two seats from the ride each day to prevent the ride from moving around in high winds during off-hours. Each time the ride opened, the seats were bolted back onto the frame of the ride. Investigators found that only one side of the victim's seat had been bolted properly, causing Margerum's seat to drop from its axle and subsequently leading to his death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/1caeec8f2c81e6f16271cc3311d3b0e9|title=Boy Killed in Fall from Ferris Wheel|website=AP NEWS}}</ref> Attendance once again began to dwindle as parents became concerned over the park's safety.\n\nCharles Wood reacquired the park along with [[The Great Escape & Splashwater Kingdom|Great Escape]] in October 1992 for $14 million dollars when International Broadcasting Corporation went bankrupt. In his second stint of ownership, Wood changed the park's name to '''Two Flags Over Niagara Fun Park,''' a name it kept until January 1994 when Martin's Shows, ran by Martin DiPietro, purchased the park and renamed it '''Martin's Fantasy Island'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/1994/01/17/area-firm-buys-two-flags-over-niagara-grand-island-amusement-complex-to-be-renamed-martins-fantasy-island/|title=AREA FIRM BUYS TWO FLAGS OVER NIAGARA GRAND ISLAND AMUSEMENT COMPLEX TO BE RENAMED 'MARTINS FANTASY ISLAND'|date=January 17, 1994}}</ref> Charles Wood took the original Comet roller coaster and reassembled it at his [[The Great Escape & Splashwater Kingdom|Great Escape]] park later that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xtrLDCJYVsAC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PA55&dq=comet+roller+coaster+%22great+escape%22+1994&pg=PA55#v=onepage&q=comet+roller+coaster+%22great+escape%22+1994&f=false|title=Western New York Amusement Parks|first=Rose Ann|last=Hirsch|date=March 2, 2011|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|via=Google Books}}</ref> DiPietro would install his own roller coaster named the [[Silver Comet (roller coaster)|Silver Comet]] in 1999 that was inspired by the original.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/2013/08/10/silver-comet-keeps-thrill-alive-for-fans-of-the-crystal-beach-roller-coaster/|title=Silver Comet keeps thrill alive for fans of the Crystal Beach roller coaster|date=August 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\nMartin DiPietro sold the park to Apex Parks Group in May 2016 and the name reverted back to '''Fantasy Island'''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fink|first=James|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/buffalo/news/2016/05/14/fantasy-island-bought-by-california-company.html|title=Fantasy Island bought by California company|work=Buffalo Business First|publisher=American City Business Journals|date=May 14, 2016|accessdate=May 14, 2016}}</ref> The transaction was funded by a loan from STORE Capital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paytax.erie.gov/webprop/property_info_history.asp?sblkey=1446000360000001019210++++&street=2400+GRAND+ISLAND+BLVD&owner=APEX+PARKS+GROUP++LLC++++|title=Real Property Information|website=paytax.erie.gov}}</ref>\n\nReports surfaced in 2018 and 2019 that the general condition of the park had deteriorated, with many attractions not operational due to either mechanical failure or under-staffing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spectrumlocalnews.com/nys/buffalo/top-stories/2018/08/18/complaints-and-petition-signatures-grow-over-fantasy-island|title=Complaints and petition signatures grow over Fantasy Island|website=spectrumlocalnews.com}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wgrz.com/article/news/local/season-pass-holders-complain-about-conditions-at-fantasy-island/71-8eaf41d2-58f2-4dcd-91d0-5ed534a3817a|title=Season pass holders complain about conditions at Fantasy Island|website=WGRZ}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, following reports that Apex Parks Group had put the park's rides up for sale, the company confirmed that the park had permanently closed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wivb.com/news/local-news/erie-county/grand-island/multiple-reports-say-fantasy-island-rides-are-being-sold/|title=Multiple reports say Fantasy Island rides are being sold|date=February 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/2020/02/19/fantasy-island-confirms-it-has-closed/|title=Fantasy Island confirms it has closed|date=February 19, 2020}}</ref> A large public outcry prompted lawmakers to demand Apex Parks Group refund the money it had already collected for season passes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wgrz.com/article/news/local/western-new-york-lawmakers-react-to-fantasy-island-refund-calls/71-403fe672-902b-4d38-94ca-f592bb89c9ae|title=Western New York lawmakers support Fantasy Island refund calls|website=WGRZ}}</ref> Apex Parks Group continued to search for a buyer for the park and noted that additional potential buyers had come forward following the announcement of the park's closure and that it would explore alternative solutions other than closing the park in cooperation with local government officials.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://wben.radio.com/articles/could-fantasy-island-make-a-comeback|title=Could Fantasy Island make a comeback?|work=[[WBEN (AM)|WBEN]]|date=February 25, 2020|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> However, trucks were seen on the property taking out restaurant equipment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wivb.com/news/local-news/fantasy-island-for-sale-owners-on-the-hook-for-undisclosed-amount/|title=Fantasy Island for sale, owners on the hook for undisclosed amount|date=February 25, 2020}}</ref> A settlement was reached with the Attorney General's office to refund customers that had prepaid for season passes.<ref>https://www.wgrz.com/article/news/local/fantasy-island-to-refund-customers-for-2020-season/71-96f1019f-c8ae-4cf0-bd36-7a96ff2f8f9d</ref>\n\n==Rides and attractions (As of 2019 closure)==\nWhen Fantasy Island last operated, the following rides and attractions were set up and operational at the park, and closed down in the fall of 2019 with the intention of reopening for the 2020 season.\n\n===Roller coasters===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Year Opened !! Removed !! Type !! Manufacturer/Model !! Comments\n|-\n| '''Crazy Mouse'''\n| 2005\n| 2020\n| [[Steel roller coaster|Steel]] Crazy Mouse Twister coaster\n| [[Zamperla]]\n| Crazy mouse with spinning cars. Replaced Wildcat in 2005 when that ride closed.\n|-\n| '''Dragon's Flight'''\n| 2019\n| 2020\n| [[Steel roller coaster|Steel]] family powered roller coaster\n| Wisdom Rides \n| Addition to Fairy tale forest for the 2019 season. Used same coaster from Beuce Carnival returned 17 years later to once again operate at Fantasy Island. \n|-\n| '''Max's Doggy Dog Coaster'''\n| 2013\n| 2020\n| [[Steel roller coaster|Steel]] kiddie roller coaster\n| [[SBF Visa Group]]\n|-\n| '''[[Silver Comet (roller coaster)|Silver Comet]]'''\n| 1999\n| 2020 SBNO\n| [[Wooden roller coaster]] \n| [[Custom Coasters International]]\n| Modeled after [[The Comet (Great Escape)|The Comet]] from [[Crystal Beach, Ontario|Crystal Beach]].\n|-\n|}\n\n===Water attractions/Rides (Splashaway Bay)===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Year Opened !! Removed !! Type !! Comments\n|-\n| '''Cannon Bowl'''\n| 2006\n| 2020 SBNO\n| ProSlide CannonBowl\n| A generic ProSlide CannonBowl water slide.\n|-\n|'''Dinosaur Pool'''\n| 1980s\n| 2020 SBNO\n| Kiddie Pool\n| A small kiddie pool with a dinosaur shaped slide in the middle of it.\n|-\n|'''Double Dare Falls'''\n| 1984\n| 2020 SBNO\n| Water Slides\n| A set of two mat water slides that cross over each other and end in a small shallow pool. Refurbished and renamed to Double Dare Falls for the 2018 season. Formerly Raging Rapids \n|-\n|'''Dragster Drench'''\n| 2012\n| 2020 SBNO\n| ProSlide ProRacer\n| A traditional four-lane racing mat slide\n|-\n|'''Splash Creek'''\n| {{N/A|Unknown}}\n| 2020 SBNO\n| Lazy River\n| A lazy river ride with water falls.\n|-\n|'''Surf Hill'''\n| 1980s\n| 2020 SBNO\n| ProSlide Water Slide\n| A small pink racing water slide for small children. On some older park maps, it's mistakenly called \"Pro-Slide.\"\n|-\n|'''Wave Pool'''\n| 1995\n| 2020 SBNO\n| Wave Pool\n| Replaced Kid Wash in 1995 when that ride closed.\n|}\n\n===Dry rides===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Year Opened !! Removed !! Manufacturer/Model !! Comments\n|-\n| '''\"Jack In The Beanstalk\"'''\n| 2015\n| 2020\n| SBF-Visa Drop n' Twist\n| Renamed \"Rapunzel! Rapunzel!\" in 2018 when Fairy Tale Forest opened.\n|-\n| '''Antique Cars'''\n| 1961\n| 2020\n| Arrow-Huss/Gould Mfg. \n| Contains original Arrow model cars, Gould cars purchased at a later date.\n|-\n| '''Balloons'''\n| 1994\n| 2020\n| Zamperla\n|\n|-\n| '''Blue Goose'''\n| 2011\n| 2020\n| Allan Herschell Company\n| Originally operated in the 1980s. Was refurbished and brought back to the park for the 50th anniversary. Renamed \"Goosey Goosey Gander\" in 2018 when Fairy Tale Forest was added.\n|-\n| '''Boats'''\n| 1961\n| 2020\n| Allan Herschell Company\n|-\n| '''Cinderella's Midnight Magic Wheel'''\n| 2018\n| 2020\n| Sartori Rides\n| Added to the park from Indiana Beach when Fairy Tale Forest Opened in 2018.\n|-\n| '''Devil's Hole'''\n| 2011\n| 2020\n| Wisdom Gravitron\n| A Rotor version of Devil's Hole that originally operated at the park until 1994. Originally, Devil's Hole was supposed to come in green which led to the Devil Statue art work to be accidentally painted green, but after that mistake was corrected, the Devil's Hole ride came in yellow and orange. Replaced Starship 2000 in 2011 when that ride closed. Located where Dragon Coaster was before that ride closed in 1986.\n|-\n| '''Flight'''\n| 2008\n| 2020\n| Zamperla Sky Flyer\n| Replaced DareDevil when that ride closed in 2001.\n|-\n|'''Full Tilt'''\n| 2007\n| 2020\n| ARM USA\n| Was Repainted in 2018 and renamed Tilt & Shout.\n|-\n| '''Gondola Wheel'''\n| 1994\n| 2020\n| Chance Rides Inc. Giant Wheel\n| Located in the back of the park across from Crazy Mouse.\n|-\n| '''Grand Carrousel'''\n| 1961\n| 2020\n| Allan Herschell Company\n| Renamed All The King's Horses when Fairy Tale Forest was added in 2018.\n|-\n| '''Grand Circus Menagerie'''\n| 2008\n| 2020\n| Sartori Rides\n| Features antique cars, motorcycles and animals.\n|-\n| '''Iron Horse'''\n| 1961\n| 2020\n| Allan Herschell Company\n| One of the park's original attractions. MFI Currently has its original engine and cars installed at the park. The Park also has the train that came from nearby Beaver Island State Park and uses that as a spare engine and cars.\n|-\n| '''Magic Ring'''\n| 1961\n| 2020\n| Zamperla\n| Features vehicles\n|-\n| '''Mega Disk'o'''\n| 2009\n| 2020\n| Zamperla\n| On February 26, 2020, local people noticed the ride was starting to get dismantled and pieces were spotted sitting in the parking lot.\n|-\n| '''Mind Warp'''\n| 2011\n| 2020\n| Technical Park Loop Fighter<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technicalpark.com/amusement-rides/loop-fighter/|title=LOOP FIGHTER|first=Technical Park Amusement|last=Rides|date=December 20, 2018}}</ref>\n| The first park model in North America. Replaced Sizzler in 2011 when that ride closed.\n|-\n| '''Red Baron'''\n| 1961\n| 2020\n| Allan Herschell Company\n| Helicopter converted. Relocated to Kiddieland.\n|-\n| '''Rio Grande Kiddy Train'''\n| 1983\n| 2020\n| Zamperla\n| Renamed Storybook Express when Fairy Tale Forest was added in 2018.\n|-\n| '''Rock & Roll Music Express'''\n| 2015\n| 2020\n| Bertazzon\n| Name often shortened to \"Rock & Roll.\"\n|-\n| '''Rockin' Tug'''\n| 2013\n| 2020\n| Zamperla\n| Located where 4X4 Truck Ride was after that ride closed in 2008; replaced Crazy Bus when that ride closed in 2013.\n|-\n| '''Scooter'''\n| 1989\n| 2020\n| Majestic TM1400 Euro Scooter\n| Was part of former owner Martin DiPietro's traveling carnival before he purchased the park in 1994 from Charles R. Wood.\n|-\n| '''Tea Cups'''\n| 2014\n| 2020\n| Zamperla Midi Tea Cups\n| Slightly larger model of the original Tea Cups, allowing adults to ride comfortably. Renamed Enchanted Tea Party when Fairy Tale Forest opened in 2018.\n|-\n| '''Tilt-A-Whirl'''\n| 1992\n| 2020\n| [[Sellner Manufacturing|Sellner]] \n|Electric 7 Tilt-A-Whirl\n|-\n|}\n\n==Former Rides and Attractions (Removed Prior to Park Closure)==\n{{Expand list|date=August 2008}}\n\n===Roller coasters===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Year Opened !! Removed !! Type !! Manufacturer/Model !! Comments\n|-\n| '''Dragon Wagon'''\n| 1994\n| 2004\n| [[Steel roller coaster|Steel]] family powered roller coaster\n| [[Zamperla|Wisdom Rides]]\n| Originally sat where Balloon Race was across from Grand Carrousel, was replaced by Orient Express and later sold to Beuce Carnival in Canada.\n|-\n| '''Little Dipper'''\n| 1961 \n| 1995\n| [[Steel roller coaster|Steel]] kiddie roller coaster\n| [[Allan Herschell Company]]\n|-\n| '''Orient Express'''\n| 1998 \n| 2004\n| [[Steel roller coaster|Steel]] kiddie roller coaster\n| Wisdom Rides\n| Replaced in 2004 by Jack and the Beanstalk. Sold to Beuce Carnival in Canada.\n|-\n| '''Wildcat'''\n| 1972\n| 2005\n| [[Steel roller coaster|Steel]] thrill roller coaster\n| [[Anton Schwarzkopf|Schwarzkopf]]\n| Replaced in 2005 with Crazy Mouse. Scrapped \n|}\n\n===Water attractions/Rides (Splashaway Bay)===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Year Opened !! Removed !! Type !! Comments\n|-\n|'''Bumper Boats'''\n| {{N/A|Unknown}}\n| {{N/A|Unknown}}\n| Bumper Boats\n| \n|-\n|'''Kid Wash'''\n| 1980s\n| 1995\n| Retro Splash Pad\n| A metal structure that kids could walk through, with dumping buckets and other squirting novelties that resembled a car wash, similar to that of a modern-day splash pad. Ride was also surrounded by smaller kiddy fountain pools, with the bumper boats at the furthest end. All removed to make way for the Wave Pool.\n|-\n|'''Old Mill Scream'''\n| 1986\n| 2014\n| Arrow Log Flume ride\n| A log flume ride with two hills. The only water ride that wasn't located in the water park area; removed due to deteriorating condition and high costs of maintenance. Originally operated at Petticoat Junction (Pirate's World) in Florida. Replaced in 2014 by Over the Falls.\n|}\n\n===Dry rides===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Year Opened !! Removed !! Manufacturer/Model !! Comments\n|-\n| '''4x4 Truck Ride'''\n| 1994\n| 2007\n| SBF Intl\n| Art work depicting some cartoon characters such as Wile E. Coyote. Was located where Rockin' Tug is now.\n|-\n| '''Astro Wheel'''\n| 1981\n| 1994\n| Chance Manufacturing\n| A skydiver converted to a Ferris Wheel. Only a handful were made. This ride spent time at Great Escape before landing here in the late 1980s. Was sold to Amusements of Buffalo which went bankrupt. The Astro wheel continues to operate today with Kissel Brothers Entertainment in the Midwest after restoration. Astro wheel was replaced by the Gondola Wheel. \n|-\n| '''Balloon Race'''\n| 1985\n| 1994\n| Zamperla\n| A bigger version of Up Up And Away. Sat where the Beanstalk currently sits today. This ride was also moved to Great Escape in 1994 when the park was sold and currently still operates there today\n|-\n| '''Bugs'''\n| 1972\n| 2011\n| Venture Manufacturing\n| A small circular ride featuring ladybugs going around a mushroom. Was in storage until end of the 2016 season when former owner Martin DiPietro took it with him as he departed from the park.\n|-\n| '''Chaos'''\n| 1997\n| 2007\n| Chance Rides Inc. \n| prototype portable version #3\n|-\n| '''Cinema 180'''\n| 1961\n| 2003\n| 3D cinema theater\n| Optical illusion film show\n|-\n| '''Crazy Bus'''\n| 1997\n| 2013\n| Zamperla \n| Replaced by Rockin' Tug\n|-\n| '''DareDevil'''\n| 2001\n| 2008\n| Chance Rides Inc. \n| Replaced with Flight.\n|-\n| '''Devil's Hole'''<ref name=\"domainofdeath3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.domainofdeath3.com/86d-rides-vol-2-hell-hole/|publisher=domainofdeath3.com|title=86&#039;d Rides vol 2: Hell Hole &#124; The DoD3|accessdate=September 7, 2016}}</ref>\n| 1975\n| 1994\n| Chance Manufacturing\n|-\n| '''Flying Bobs'''\n| 1989\n| 2003\n| Chance Rides Inc. \n| Purchased in auction from Crystal Beach when it closed in 1989. Sold to an unknown location in Mexico.\n|-\n| '''Giant Slide'''\n| 1975\n| 2018\n| Slide\n| Manufactured by Whitehead Plastics.\n|-\n| '''Jack and the Beanstalk'''\n| 2004\n| 2015\n| Moser \n| Spring Ride. Themed after the beanstalk statue located near the ride. Replaced Orient Express in 2004 when that ride closed.\n|-\n| '''Nitro'''\n| 2003\n| 2009\n| Zamperla \n| Ride removed due to foundational issues because of its portable nature.\n|-\n| '''Over The Falls'''\n| 2014\n| 2015\n| KMG Speed\n| The largest ride in park history at approximately 131 feet tall. Replaced Old Mill Scream in 2014 when that ride closed.\n|-\n| '''Paratrooper'''\n| 1975\n| 1994\n| Hrubetz \n| Was sold to Amusements of Buffalo which went bankrupt. It's now in Michigan with a traveling carnival. \n|-\n| '''Patriot'''\n| 1989\n| 2009\n| ARM-UK\n| After the 2008 season, the Patriot was sold; however, improper handling led to a hydraulic cylinder bursting, causing the ride to collapse. Full Tilt was then moved to its current location in 2009 to make way for Mega Disk-O.\n|-\n| '''Rampage'''\n| 1979\n| 1984\n| Watkins\n| this was an originally a trailer-mounted ride.\n|-\n| '''Rok O Plane'''\n| 1975\n| 1998\n| Eyerly aircraft\n| Came from Martin's Shows\n|-\n| '''Scooter'''\n| 1989\n| 2020\n| Majestic TM1400 Euro Scooter\n| Was part of former owner Martin DiPietro's traveling carnival before he purchased the park in 1994 from Charles R. Wood.\n|-\n| '''Sea Ray'''\n| 1995\n| 2011\n| Mulligan Engineering\n|\n|-\n| '''Sizzler'''\n| 1989\n| 2011\n| Wisdom Rides\n| A Scrambler style ride. Replaced with Mind Warp in 2011.\n|-\n| '''Space Shuttle'''\n| 1961\n| 1994\n| Chance Manufacturing\n| A swinging ship ride that was made to look like a rocket ship. Was sold to Amusements of Buffalo which went bankrupt. It's unknown of where this ride is today. \n|-\n|'''Space Whirl'''\n| 1962\n| 1976\n| Arrow Development\n| Jet ride. Purchased from the 1961 World's Fair in Seattle.\n|-\n| '''Starship 2000'''\n| 2009\n| 2011\n| Wisdom Rides\n| Replaced with Devil's Hole when it returned in 2011. Was leased from Wisdom Rides.\n|-\n| '''Super Spiral'''\n| 1977\n| 2002\n| Hrubetz\n| Round up\n|-\n| '''Tea Cups'''\n| 1997\n| 2014\n| Zamperla mini Tea Cups\n| Replaced in 2014 by a larger model like the ones at Seabreeze in Rochester, New York and Lagoon in Farmington, Utah.\n|-\n| '''Tranbant'''\n| 1961\n| 1994\n| Chance Manufacturing\n| Located next to where the games building is now. Moved to Great Escape but no longer operates. It's now a dining platform. \n|-\n| '''YoYo'''\n| 1961\n| 1994\n| Chance Manufacturing\n| A chair swing style ride. Was sold to and restored by Amusements of Buffalo which went bankrupt. The ride was auctioned off and now sits at Quassy Amusement Park in the Northeast. \n|}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nimage:silver comet station.jpg|The silver comet roller coaster\nimage:Devil's Hole.jpg|The [[Gravitron]] version of Devil's Hole\nImage:Mega Disk'O.jpg|A [[Zamperla]] Mega Disk'O ride\nimage:Indian Village.jpg|The Indian Village\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.fantasyislandny.com Official website]\n*{{RCDB|4732}}\n\n[[Category:1961 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:2020 disestablishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Abandoned amusement parks in the United States]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks opened in 1961]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks closed in 2020]]\n[[Category:Defunct amusement parks in the United States]]\n[[Category:Defunct amusement parks in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox amusement park\n| name = Fantasy Island\n| logo            = Fantasy Island Grand Island logo.png\n| logo_size       = \n| alt             = \n| logo_caption    = \n| image           = \n| image_size      =\n| slogan   = Fun. Done. Right.<small> (2016-2020)</small><br>50 Years of Family Fun<small> (2011-2016)</small><br>Spend the Day, Not a Fortune<small> (1994-2011)</small><br>Makes a Good Time Great!<small> (1986-1992)</small><br>Celebrate<small> (1982-1986)</small><br>Fun? Wow!<small> (1978-1982)</small><br>A Dream Come True<small> (1961-1978)</small>\n| location = 2400 Grand Island Boulevard\n| location2 = [[Grand Island, New York|Grand Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]] 14072\n| area = {{convert|85|acre|m2}}\n| status          = Closed \n| opening_date = July 1, 1961\n| closing_date    = February 19, 2020\n| previous_names  = Two Flags Over Niagara Fun Park <small>(1992-1994)</small><br>Martin's Fantasy Island <small>(1994\u20132016)</small>\n| owner = [[Apex Parks Group]] <small>(2016-2020)</small><br>Martin's Shows <small>(1994-2016) </small><br>International Broadcasting Corporation <small>(1989-1992)</small><br>[[Charles Wood (businessman)|Charles R. Wood Enterprises]] <small>(1982-1989, 1992-1994)</small><br>Fantasy Island, Inc. <small>(1961-1982)</small>\n| general_manager = \n| homepage = [http://www.fantasyislandny.com Official website]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|43|1|37.2|N|78|58|14.5|W|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Fantasy Island''' was an [[amusement park]] on [[Grand Island, New York]] from 1961 to 2020.\n\n==History==\n'''Fantasy Island''' was founded by real estate developer Lawrence Grant and opened in July 1961. It was designed by co-financier Gerald Birzon, a local jeweler, and constructed by Milton Milstein and Associates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MKOkQoVeGWAC&lpg=PA157&ots=dI3UV6pHqt&dq=%22Lawrence+Grant%22+%22fantasy+island%22&pg=PA157#v=onepage&q=%22Lawrence+Grant%22+%22fantasy+island%22&f=false|title=Amusement Parks of New York|first=Jim|last=Futrell|date=March 2, 2006|publisher=Stackpole Books|via=Google Books}}</ref> The ownership group was formed under the name Fantasy Land, Inc. before changing soon after to Fantasy Island, Inc. The group had originally planned to call the park '''Fantasy Land''', but changed the name for legal reasons after finding out there was already an area of [[Disneyland]] called [[Fantasyland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xtrLDCJYVsAC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PA77&dq=%22fantasy+land,+inc%22&pg=PA77#v=onepage&q=%22fantasy+land,+inc%22&f=false|title=Western New York Amusement Parks|first=Rose Ann|last=Hirsch|date=March 2, 2011|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nOriginally, the park occupied only {{convert|12|acre|m2}} of land that was divided into five themed areas: Action Town, Animal Kingdom, Garden of Fables, Indian Village, and Western Town.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/2011/07/08/theme-park-to-mark-50th-year-fantasy-island-plans-saturday-celebration/|title=Theme park to mark 50th year; Fantasy Island plans Saturday celebration|date=July 8, 2011}}</ref>  Western Town, a live [[Wild West shows|Wild West show]], remained a staple of the park throughout its existence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wgrz.com/article/entertainment/television/programs/most-buffalo/fantasy-island-reunion-western-town-alumni-reunite/71-81f6e7f9-260a-4979-8118-89a90a34a85a|title=Fantasy Island reunion: 'Western Town' alumni reunite|first=Pete|last=Gallivan|first2=Kate|last2=Welshofer|work=[[WGRZ]]|date=March 2, 2020|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> \n\nTo promote the park, [[WGR-TV]] aired a live weekly television program on Saturday mornings from 1961 to 1962 titled '''''Fantasy Island Show'''''. It featured the park's characters and puppeteers performing for an all-children studio audience. The show's host and protagonist was Buckskin Joe, portrayed by park general manager Clyde \"Buddy\" Farnan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.buffalostories.com/the-golden-age-of-kids-tv-in-buffalo/|title=The Golden Age of Kids\u2019 TV in Buffalo \u2013 Buffalo Stories Archives & Blog}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xtrLDCJYVsAC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PA87&dq=%22fantasy+island%22+wgr&pg=PA87#v=onepage&q=%22fantasy+island%22+wgr&f=false|title=Western New York Amusement Parks|first=Rose Ann|last=Hirsch|date=March 2, 2011|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nA 2,500-seat outdoor arena was constructed in 1965 for French [[lion tamer]] Jean \"Tarzan\" Zerbini's circus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MKOkQoVeGWAC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PA158&dq=%22fantasy+island%22+zerbini&pg=PA158#v=onepage&q=%22fantasy+island%22+zerbini&f=false|title=Amusement Parks of New York|first=Jim|last=Futrell|date=March 2, 2006|publisher=Stackpole Books|via=Google Books}}</ref> The park was expanded to {{convert|85|acre|m2}} in 1974 to make room for adult rides and broaden the park's appeal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MKOkQoVeGWAC&lpg=PA160&ots=dI3UV6qEpt&dq=%22fantasy+island%22+1974+%2285+acres%22&pg=PA160#v=onepage&q=%22fantasy+island%22+1974+%2285+acres%22&f=false|title=Amusement Parks of New York|first=Jim|last=Futrell|date=March 2, 2006|publisher=Stackpole Books|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nAfter dwindling attendance stemming from Western New York's [[rust belt]] economic decline, Fantasy Island, Inc. declared bankruptcy and the park did not operate for the 1982 season. It was acquired out of bankruptcy in November 1982 by Charles R. Wood Enterprises, headed by [[Charles Wood (businessman)|Charles Wood]], the founder of [[The Great Escape & Splashwater Kingdom|Great Escape]] in [[Queensbury, New York]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1982/11/23/Youngsters-need-those-summer-jobs/9758406875600/|title='Youngsters need those summer jobs'|website=UPI}}</ref> A new themed area called Water World, a [[water park]], was added to the site in 1984. Wood sold the park along with [[The Great Escape & Splashwater Kingdom|Great Escape]] to International Broadcasting Corporation (IBC) in April 1989 for $36 million dollars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MKOkQoVeGWAC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PA163&dq=%22international+broadcasting+corporation%22+%22fantasy+island%22&pg=PA163#v=onepage&q=%22international+broadcasting+corporation%22+%22fantasy+island%22&f=false|title=Amusement Parks of New York|first=Jim|last=Futrell|date=March 2, 2006|publisher=Stackpole Books|via=Google Books}}</ref> As part of the deal, Wood wood stay on as [[chief executive officer]] of the park and his son-in-law, Tom Wages, was retained as general manager.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://casetext.com/case/international-broadcasting-v-turner|title=International Broadcasting v. Turner, 734 F. Supp. 383 &#124; Casetext|website=casetext.com}}</ref> Following the closure of nearby [[Crystal Beach Amusement Park]], that park's famed [[Comet (Great Escape)|Comet]] roller coaster was purchased by Charles Wood at auction in October 1989 for $210,000, disassembled, and stored indefinitely at Fantasy Island.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/1989/10/18/the-comet-is-going-going-but-might-not-be-gone-210000-sale-may-bring-it-to-fantasy-island/|title=THE COMET IS GOING, GOING . . . BUT MIGHT NOT BE GONE $210,000 SALE MAY BRING IT TO FANTASY ISLAND|date=October 18, 1989}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1990, Michael Murach was paralyzed from the head down while performing a [[high diving]] act at the park. He slipped on a 3-meter diving board during a comedy act and fell 20-feet, hitting his head on the edge of the concrete pool. Murach was years later awarded damages of $58.6 million dollars after a jury found International Broadcasting Corporation 100% liable for his injury. The end of the diving board was not installed at a proper distance away from the edge of the pool to prevent such an incident from occurring. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/2003/12/03/paralyzed-ex-diver-awarded-58-6-million/|title=PARALYZED EX-DIVER AWARDED $58.6 MILLION|date=December 3, 2003}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1991, 14-year-old Kenneth Margerum fell {{convert|60|ft}} to his death from the park's [[Ferris wheel]] after his seat dropped from its axle. It was revealed that the park operators routinely removed one or two seats from the ride each day to prevent the ride from moving around in high winds during off-hours. Each time the ride opened, the seats were bolted back onto the frame of the ride. Investigators found that only one side of the victim's seat had been bolted properly, causing Margerum's seat to drop from its axle and subsequently leading to his death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/1caeec8f2c81e6f16271cc3311d3b0e9|title=Boy Killed in Fall from Ferris Wheel|website=AP NEWS}}</ref> Attendance once again began to dwindle as parents became concerned over the park's safety.\n\nCharles Wood reacquired the park along with [[The Great Escape & Splashwater Kingdom|Great Escape]] in October 1992 for $14 million dollars when International Broadcasting Corporation went bankrupt. In his second stint of ownership, Wood changed the park's name to '''Two Flags Over Niagara Fun Park,''' a name it kept until January 1994 when Martin's Shows, ran by Martin DiPietro, purchased the park and renamed it '''Martin's Fantasy Island'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/1994/01/17/area-firm-buys-two-flags-over-niagara-grand-island-amusement-complex-to-be-renamed-martins-fantasy-island/|title=AREA FIRM BUYS TWO FLAGS OVER NIAGARA GRAND ISLAND AMUSEMENT COMPLEX TO BE RENAMED 'MARTINS FANTASY ISLAND'|date=January 17, 1994}}</ref> Charles Wood took the original Comet roller coaster and reassembled it at his [[The Great Escape & Splashwater Kingdom|Great Escape]] park later that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xtrLDCJYVsAC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&lpg=PA55&dq=comet+roller+coaster+%22great+escape%22+1994&pg=PA55#v=onepage&q=comet+roller+coaster+%22great+escape%22+1994&f=false|title=Western New York Amusement Parks|first=Rose Ann|last=Hirsch|date=March 2, 2011|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|via=Google Books}}</ref> DiPietro would install his own roller coaster named the [[Silver Comet (roller coaster)|Silver Comet]] in 1999 that was inspired by the original.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/2013/08/10/silver-comet-keeps-thrill-alive-for-fans-of-the-crystal-beach-roller-coaster/|title=Silver Comet keeps thrill alive for fans of the Crystal Beach roller coaster|date=August 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\nMartin DiPietro sold the park to Apex Parks Group in May 2016 and the name reverted back to '''Fantasy Island'''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fink|first=James|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/buffalo/news/2016/05/14/fantasy-island-bought-by-california-company.html|title=Fantasy Island bought by California company|work=Buffalo Business First|publisher=American City Business Journals|date=May 14, 2016|accessdate=May 14, 2016}}</ref> The transaction was funded by a loan from STORE Capital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paytax.erie.gov/webprop/property_info_history.asp?sblkey=1446000360000001019210++++&street=2400+GRAND+ISLAND+BLVD&owner=APEX+PARKS+GROUP++LLC++++|title=Real Property Information|website=paytax.erie.gov}}</ref>\n\nReports surfaced in 2018 and 2019 that the general condition of the park had deteriorated, with many attractions not operational due to either mechanical failure or under-staffing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spectrumlocalnews.com/nys/buffalo/top-stories/2018/08/18/complaints-and-petition-signatures-grow-over-fantasy-island|title=Complaints and petition signatures grow over Fantasy Island|website=spectrumlocalnews.com}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wgrz.com/article/news/local/season-pass-holders-complain-about-conditions-at-fantasy-island/71-8eaf41d2-58f2-4dcd-91d0-5ed534a3817a|title=Season pass holders complain about conditions at Fantasy Island|website=WGRZ}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, following reports that Apex Parks Group had put the park's rides up for sale, the company confirmed that the park had permanently closed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wivb.com/news/local-news/erie-county/grand-island/multiple-reports-say-fantasy-island-rides-are-being-sold/|title=Multiple reports say Fantasy Island rides are being sold|date=February 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/2020/02/19/fantasy-island-confirms-it-has-closed/|title=Fantasy Island confirms it has closed|date=February 19, 2020}}</ref> A large public outcry prompted lawmakers to demand Apex Parks Group refund the money it had already collected for season passes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wgrz.com/article/news/local/western-new-york-lawmakers-react-to-fantasy-island-refund-calls/71-403fe672-902b-4d38-94ca-f592bb89c9ae|title=Western New York lawmakers support Fantasy Island refund calls|website=WGRZ}}</ref> Apex Parks Group continued to search for a buyer for the park and noted that additional potential buyers had come forward following the announcement of the park's closure and that it would explore alternative solutions other than closing the park in cooperation with local government officials.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://wben.radio.com/articles/could-fantasy-island-make-a-comeback|title=Could Fantasy Island make a comeback?|work=[[WBEN (AM)|WBEN]]|date=February 25, 2020|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> However, trucks were seen on the property taking out restaurant equipment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wivb.com/news/local-news/fantasy-island-for-sale-owners-on-the-hook-for-undisclosed-amount/|title=Fantasy Island for sale, owners on the hook for undisclosed amount|date=February 25, 2020}}</ref> A settlement was reached with the Attorney General's office to refund customers that had prepaid for season passes.<ref>https://www.wgrz.com/article/news/local/fantasy-island-to-refund-customers-for-2020-season/71-96f1019f-c8ae-4cf0-bd36-7a96ff2f8f9d</ref>\n\n==Rides and attractions (As of 2019 closure)==\n{{Expand list|date=August 2008}}\n\n===Roller coasters===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Year Opened !! Removed !! Type !! Manufacturer/Model !! Comments\n|-\n| '''Crazy Mouse'''\n| 2005\n| 2020\n| [[Steel roller coaster|Steel]] Crazy Mouse Twister coaster\n| [[Zamperla]]\n| Crazy mouse with spinning cars. Replaced Wildcat in 2005 when that ride closed.\n|-\n| '''Dragon's Flight'''\n| 2019\n| 2020\n| [[Steel roller coaster|Steel]] family powered roller coaster\n| Wisdom Rides \n| Addition to Fairy tale forest for the 2019 season. Used same coaster from Beuce Carnival returned 17 years later to once again operate at Fantasy Island. \n|-\n| '''Max's Doggy Dog Coaster'''\n| 2013\n| 2020\n| [[Steel roller coaster|Steel]] kiddie roller coaster\n| [[SBF Visa Group]]\n|-\n| '''[[Silver Comet (roller coaster)|Silver Comet]]'''\n| 1999\n| 2020 SBNO\n| [[Wooden roller coaster]] \n| [[Custom Coasters International]]\n| Modeled after [[The Comet (Great Escape)|The Comet]] from [[Crystal Beach, Ontario|Crystal Beach]].\n|-\n|}\n\n===Water attractions/Rides (Splashaway Bay)===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Year Opened !! Removed !! Type !! Comments\n|-\n| '''Cannon Bowl'''\n| 2006\n| 2020 SBNO\n| ProSlide CannonBowl\n| A generic ProSlide CannonBowl water slide.\n|-\n|'''Dinosaur Pool'''\n| 1980s\n| 2020 SBNO\n| Kiddie Pool\n| A small kiddie pool with a dinosaur shaped slide in the middle of it.\n|-\n|'''Double Dare Falls'''\n| 1984\n| 2020 SBNO\n| Water Slides\n| A set of two mat water slides that cross over each other and end in a small shallow pool. Refurbished and renamed to Double Dare Falls for the 2018 season. Formerly Raging Rapids \n|-\n|'''Dragster Drench'''\n| 2012\n| 2020 SBNO\n| ProSlide ProRacer\n| A traditional four-lane racing mat slide\n|-\n|'''Splash Creek'''\n| {{N/A|Unknown}}\n| 2020 SBNO\n| Lazy River\n| A lazy river ride with water falls.\n|-\n|'''Surf Hill'''\n| 1980s\n| 2020 SBNO\n| ProSlide Water Slide\n| A small pink racing water slide for small children. On some older park maps, it's mistakenly called \"Pro-Slide.\"\n|-\n|'''Wave Pool'''\n| 1995\n| 2020 SBNO\n| Wave Pool\n| Replaced Kid Wash in 1995 when that ride closed.\n|}\n\n===Dry rides===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Year Opened !! Removed !! Manufacturer/Model !! Comments\n|-\n| '''\"Jack In The Beanstalk\"'''\n| 2015\n| 2020\n| SBF-Visa Drop n' Twist\n| Renamed \"Rapunzel! Rapunzel!\" in 2018 when Fairy Tale Forest opened.\n|-\n| '''Antique Cars'''\n| 1961\n| 2020\n| Arrow-Huss/Gould Mfg. \n| Contains original Arrow model cars, Gould cars purchased at a later date.\n|-\n| '''Balloons'''\n| 1994\n| 2020\n| Zamperla\n|\n|-\n| '''Blue Goose'''\n| 2011\n| 2020\n| Allan Herschell Company\n| Originally operated in the 1980s. Was refurbished and brought back to the park for the 50th anniversary. Renamed \"Goosey Goosey Gander\" in 2018 when Fairy Tale Forest was added.\n|-\n| '''Boats'''\n| 1961\n| 2020\n| Allan Herschell Company\n|-\n| '''Cinderella's Midnight Magic Wheel'''\n| 2018\n| 2020\n| Sartori Rides\n| Added to the park from Indiana Beach when Fairy Tale Forest Opened in 2018.\n|-\n| '''Devil's Hole'''\n| 2011\n| 2020\n| Wisdom Gravitron\n| A Rotor version of Devil's Hole that originally operated at the park until 1994. Originally, Devil's Hole was supposed to come in green which led to the Devil Statue art work to be accidentally painted green, but after that mistake was corrected, the Devil's Hole ride came in yellow and orange. Replaced Starship 2000 in 2011 when that ride closed. Located where Dragon Coaster was before that ride closed in 1986.\n|-\n| '''Flight'''\n| 2008\n| 2020\n| Zamperla Sky Flyer\n| Replaced DareDevil when that ride closed in 2001.\n|-\n|'''Full Tilt'''\n| 2007\n| 2020\n| ARM USA\n| Was Repainted in 2018 and renamed Tilt & Shout.\n|-\n| '''Gondola Wheel'''\n| 1994\n| 2020\n| Chance Rides Inc. Giant Wheel\n| Located in the back of the park across from Crazy Mouse.\n|-\n| '''Grand Carrousel'''\n| 1961\n| 2020\n| Allan Herschell Company\n| Renamed All The King's Horses when Fairy Tale Forest was added in 2018.\n|-\n| '''Grand Circus Menagerie'''\n| 2008\n| 2020\n| Sartori Rides\n| Features antique cars, motorcycles and animals.\n|-\n| '''Iron Horse'''\n| 1961\n| 2020\n| Allan Herschell Company\n| One of the park's original attractions. MFI Currently has its original engine and cars installed at the park. The Park also has the train that came from nearby Beaver Island State Park and uses that as a spare engine and cars.\n|-\n| '''Magic Ring'''\n| 1961\n| 2020\n| Zamperla\n| Features vehicles\n|-\n| '''Mega Disk'o'''\n| 2009\n| 2020\n| Zamperla\n| On February 26, 2020, local people noticed the ride was starting to get dismantled and pieces were spotted sitting in the parking lot.\n|-\n| '''Mind Warp'''\n| 2011\n| 2020\n| Technical Park Loop Fighter<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technicalpark.com/amusement-rides/loop-fighter/|title=LOOP FIGHTER|first=Technical Park Amusement|last=Rides|date=December 20, 2018}}</ref>\n| The first park model in North America. Replaced Sizzler in 2011 when that ride closed.\n|-\n| '''Red Baron'''\n| 1961\n| 2020\n| Allan Herschell Company\n| Helicopter converted. Relocated to Kiddieland.\n|-\n| '''Rio Grande Kiddy Train'''\n| 1983\n| 2020\n| Zamperla\n| Renamed Storybook Express when Fairy Tale Forest was added in 2018.\n|-\n| '''Rock & Roll Music Express'''\n| 2015\n| 2020\n| Bertazzon\n| Name often shortened to \"Rock & Roll.\"\n|-\n| '''Rockin' Tug'''\n| 2013\n| 2020\n| Zamperla\n| Located where 4X4 Truck Ride was after that ride closed in 2008; replaced Crazy Bus when that ride closed in 2013.\n|-\n| '''Scooter'''\n| 1989\n| 2020\n| Majestic TM1400 Euro Scooter\n| Was part of former owner Martin DiPietro's traveling carnival before he purchased the park in 1994 from Charles R. Wood.\n|-\n| '''Tea Cups'''\n| 2014\n| 2020\n| Zamperla Midi Tea Cups\n| Slightly larger model of the original Tea Cups, allowing adults to ride comfortably. Renamed Enchanted Tea Party when Fairy Tale Forest opened in 2018.\n|-\n| '''Tilt-A-Whirl'''\n| 1992\n| 2020\n| [[Sellner Manufacturing|Sellner]] \n|Electric 7 Tilt-A-Whirl\n|-\n|}\n\n==Former Rides and Attractions (Removed Prior to Park Closure)==\n{{Expand list|date=August 2008}}\n\n===Roller coasters===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Year Opened !! Removed !! Type !! Manufacturer/Model !! Comments\n|-\n| '''Dragon Wagon'''\n| 1994\n| 2004\n| [[Steel roller coaster|Steel]] family powered roller coaster\n| [[Zamperla|Wisdom Rides]]\n| Originally sat where Balloon Race was across from Grand Carrousel, was replaced by Orient Express and later sold to Beuce Carnival in Canada.\n|-\n| '''Little Dipper'''\n| 1961 \n| 1995\n| [[Steel roller coaster|Steel]] kiddie roller coaster\n| [[Allan Herschell Company]]\n|-\n| '''Orient Express'''\n| 1998 \n| 2004\n| [[Steel roller coaster|Steel]] kiddie roller coaster\n| Wisdom Rides\n| Replaced in 2004 by Jack and the Beanstalk. Sold to Beuce Carnival in Canada.\n|-\n| '''Wildcat'''\n| 1972\n| 2005\n| [[Steel roller coaster|Steel]] thrill roller coaster\n| [[Anton Schwarzkopf|Schwarzkopf]]\n| Replaced in 2005 with Crazy Mouse. Scrapped \n|}\n\n===Water attractions/Rides (Splashaway Bay)===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Year Opened !! Removed !! Type !! Comments\n|-\n|'''Bumper Boats'''\n| {{N/A|Unknown}}\n| {{N/A|Unknown}}\n| Bumper Boats\n| \n|-\n|'''Kid Wash'''\n| 1980s\n| 1995\n| Retro Splash Pad\n| A metal structure that kids could walk through, with dumping buckets and other squirting novelties that resembled a car wash, similar to that of a modern-day splash pad. Ride was also surrounded by smaller kiddy fountain pools, with the bumper boats at the furthest end. All removed to make way for the Wave Pool.\n|-\n|'''Old Mill Scream'''\n| 1986\n| 2014\n| Arrow Log Flume ride\n| A log flume ride with two hills. The only water ride that wasn't located in the water park area; removed due to deteriorating condition and high costs of maintenance. Originally operated at Petticoat Junction (Pirate's World) in Florida. Replaced in 2014 by Over the Falls.\n|}\n\n===Dry rides===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Year Opened !! Removed !! Manufacturer/Model !! Comments\n|-\n| '''4x4 Truck Ride'''\n| 1994\n| 2007\n| SBF Intl\n| Art work depicting some cartoon characters such as Wile E. Coyote. Was located where Rockin' Tug is now.\n|-\n| '''Astro Wheel'''\n| 1981\n| 1994\n| Chance Manufacturing\n| A skydiver converted to a Ferris Wheel. Only a handful were made. This ride spent time at Great Escape before landing here in the late 1980s. Was sold to Amusements of Buffalo which went bankrupt. The Astro wheel continues to operate today with Kissel Brothers Entertainment in the Midwest after restoration. Astro wheel was replaced by the Gondola Wheel. \n|-\n| '''Balloon Race'''\n| 1985\n| 1994\n| Zamperla\n| A bigger version of Up Up And Away. Sat where the Beanstalk currently sits today. This ride was also moved to Great Escape in 1994 when the park was sold and currently still operates there today\n|-\n| '''Bugs'''\n| 1972\n| 2011\n| Venture Manufacturing\n| A small circular ride featuring ladybugs going around a mushroom. Was in storage until end of the 2016 season when former owner Martin DiPietro took it with him as he departed from the park.\n|-\n| '''Chaos'''\n| 1997\n| 2007\n| Chance Rides Inc. \n| prototype portable version #3\n|-\n| '''Cinema 180'''\n| 1961\n| 2003\n| 3D cinema theater\n| Optical illusion film show\n|-\n| '''Crazy Bus'''\n| 1997\n| 2013\n| Zamperla \n| Replaced by Rockin' Tug\n|-\n| '''DareDevil'''\n| 2001\n| 2008\n| Chance Rides Inc. \n| Replaced with Flight.\n|-\n| '''Devil's Hole'''<ref name=\"domainofdeath3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.domainofdeath3.com/86d-rides-vol-2-hell-hole/|publisher=domainofdeath3.com|title=86&#039;d Rides vol 2: Hell Hole &#124; The DoD3|accessdate=September 7, 2016}}</ref>\n| 1975\n| 1994\n| Chance Manufacturing\n|-\n| '''Flying Bobs'''\n| 1989\n| 2003\n| Chance Rides Inc. \n| Purchased in auction from Crystal Beach when it closed in 1989. Sold to an unknown location in Mexico.\n|-\n| '''Giant Slide'''\n| 1975\n| 2018\n| Slide\n| Manufactured by Whitehead Plastics.\n|-\n| '''Jack and the Beanstalk'''\n| 2004\n| 2015\n| Moser \n| Spring Ride. Themed after the beanstalk statue located near the ride. Replaced Orient Express in 2004 when that ride closed.\n|-\n| '''Nitro'''\n| 2003\n| 2009\n| Zamperla \n| Ride removed due to foundational issues because of its portable nature.\n|-\n| '''Over The Falls'''\n| 2014\n| 2015\n| KMG Speed\n| The largest ride in park history at approximately 131 feet tall. Replaced Old Mill Scream in 2014 when that ride closed.\n|-\n| '''Paratrooper'''\n| 1975\n| 1994\n| Hrubetz \n| Was sold to Amusements of Buffalo which went bankrupt. It's now in Michigan with a traveling carnival. \n|-\n| '''Patriot'''\n| 1989\n| 2009\n| ARM-UK\n| After the 2008 season, the Patriot was sold; however, improper handling led to a hydraulic cylinder bursting, causing the ride to collapse. Full Tilt was then moved to its current location in 2009 to make way for Mega Disk-O.\n|-\n| '''Rampage'''\n| 1979\n| 1984\n| Watkins\n| this was an originally a trailer-mounted ride.\n|-\n| '''Rok O Plane'''\n| 1975\n| 1998\n| Eyerly aircraft\n| Came from Martin's Shows\n|-\n| '''Scooter'''\n| 1989\n| 2020\n| Majestic TM1400 Euro Scooter\n| Was part of former owner Martin DiPietro's traveling carnival before he purchased the park in 1994 from Charles R. Wood.\n|-\n| '''Sea Ray'''\n| 1995\n| 2011\n| Mulligan Engineering\n|\n|-\n| '''Sizzler'''\n| 1989\n| 2011\n| Wisdom Rides\n| A Scrambler style ride. Replaced with Mind Warp in 2011.\n|-\n| '''Space Shuttle'''\n| 1961\n| 1994\n| Chance Manufacturing\n| A swinging ship ride that was made to look like a rocket ship. Was sold to Amusements of Buffalo which went bankrupt. It's unknown of where this ride is today. \n|-\n|'''Space Whirl'''\n| 1962\n| 1976\n| Arrow Development\n| Jet ride. Purchased from the 1961 World's Fair in Seattle.\n|-\n| '''Starship 2000'''\n| 2009\n| 2011\n| Wisdom Rides\n| Replaced with Devil's Hole when it returned in 2011. Was leased from Wisdom Rides.\n|-\n| '''Super Spiral'''\n| 1977\n| 2002\n| Hrubetz\n| Round up\n|-\n| '''Tea Cups'''\n| 1997\n| 2014\n| Zamperla mini Tea Cups\n| Replaced in 2014 by a larger model like the ones at Seabreeze in Rochester, New York and Lagoon in Farmington, Utah.\n|-\n| '''Tranbant'''\n| 1961\n| 1994\n| Chance Manufacturing\n| Located next to where the games building is now. Moved to Great Escape but no longer operates. It's now a dining platform. \n|-\n| '''YoYo'''\n| 1961\n| 1994\n| Chance Manufacturing\n| A chair swing style ride. Was sold to and restored by Amusements of Buffalo which went bankrupt. The ride was auctioned off and now sits at Quassy Amusement Park in the Northeast. \n|}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nimage:silver comet station.jpg|The silver comet roller coaster\nimage:Devil's Hole.jpg|The [[Gravitron]] version of Devil's Hole\nImage:Mega Disk'O.jpg|A [[Zamperla]] Mega Disk'O ride\nimage:Indian Village.jpg|The Indian Village\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.fantasyislandny.com Official website]\n*{{RCDB|4732}}\n\n[[Category:1961 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:2020 disestablishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Abandoned amusement parks in the United States]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks opened in 1961]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks closed in 2020]]\n[[Category:Defunct amusement parks in the United States]]\n[[Category:Defunct amusement parks in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Bigtime Boy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRides and attractions (As of 2019 closure)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fantasy_Island_(U.S._amusement_park)"}
